<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Summit Power Captain U</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Summit Power Group (CCS0046)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Summit Power welcomes the opportunity to provide input to the committee on CCS. The development of CCS is fundamental</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to the UK and international ability to mitigate the effects of climate change whilst delivering society’s energy needs. CCS is complimentary to other low carbon energy sources such as renewables and nuclear.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Summit Power has been focused on the developme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nt of CCS projects for the last ten years and has in the last 3 years focused in the UK to develop a sister plant to its project in  Texas – the Texas Clean Energy Project (TCEP). Summit Power entered the UK in anticipation of DEMO 2-4 in 2011 when Longann</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">et was in FEED. As such, we are perhaps unique in bringing a perspective of the challenges the industry faces to get CCS started.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Summit Power and CO2DeepStore are joint developers of the proposed Captain Clean Energy Project(CCEP), a new build IGCC plant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> at Grangemouth on the Forth Estuary. The developers are in discussion with DECC about the project.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Summit Power offers the following input to the committee;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.05pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">CCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">pre-combustion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">technology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> on coal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is well-proven in different applications and there are no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">technology challenges preventing its deployment at scale. CO2 capture, transport and storage can be delivered safely and effectively. CCS will be very cost-competitive with other low-carbon technologies.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are concerned that the DECC CCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Commercialisation Programme Competition (Demo 2) is taking much longer than originally indicated. The programme commenced in January 2012 with calls for expressions of interest; bid process in April and submission in July with intention of FEED award at th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e end of 2012. We are now approaching the end of 2013 with still no finalization of FEED contracts with the 2 preferred bidder</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Although the UK has a very good package for CCS in the form of FEED funding, capital grant and CFD, it is not clear whether the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">se projects will enter FEED or reach FID. It is very important for the CCS industry for the projects to enter FEED and allow DECC to focus on delivering their desired outcome of commercializing CCS in the 2020’s.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">CCEP continues as a reserve bidder in DEMO </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2 until such time as the competition completes. CCEP has at the request of the then Energy Minister (John Hayes), attempted to progress the project outside of the competition under the EMR transitional arrangements (FIDe). The project provided its Offer to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> progress the project through FEED with no required funding from DECC for both FEED or Construction and rely purely on the CFD. We are making very slow progress with DECC to receive any affirmation that DECC would be willing to enter into negotiations to a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">llocate a CFD for non DEMO 2 projects </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in the near term. At best the process for negotiation may start in 2q 2014 when the Energy Minister has provided concurrence to offer CFD’s in principle to non competition projects. We have been working with DECC since</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> August 2013 to define the business case.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">With 2-3 projects available to progress outside of the competition, it is unclear why DECC is unwilling to progress these projects in parallel to DEMO 2 projects given this would provide increased optionality of wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ich projects to progress to construction at the end of FEED with no additional cost/draw of funds.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DECC’s actions and delay in DEMO 2 have significantly affected investor willingness to consider the UK given on paper it has a great offering compared to oth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">er nations. Given recent IPCC reports and work to highlight the significant cost of not doing CCS but relying on Nuclear or Renewables, the opportunity to make progress beyond DEMO2 is now.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Without an increase in ambition and acceleration or change in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">way DECC currently handles CCS, there is a significant risk that all 4-5 of the UK CCS projects currently being contemplated will fall away and the UK will have no operational CCS projects in the foreseeable future.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Such an outcome will either mean significant extra costs for the consumer (relying on other forms of low carbon power) or prevent the UK from meeting its carbon reduction targets, miss an opportunity for UK economic growth, miss an opportunity to export CC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">S skills and products and result in significant wasted effort in government. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">CCEP is a project which can act as a catalyst for utilizing CO2 for Enhanced Oil Recovery in the UK North Sea. This opportunity will be lost if we do not start implementing CCS i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">n those locations that maximize the value of CO2. The longer  we wait, the more likely it will be that oil fields will have been decommissioned and the economic opportunity lost.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The UK needs to invest in infrastructure and CCS provides that opportunity. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e do not understand the reluctance of DECC to progress technically proven, financeable and available projects that create significant economic value in excess of their cost under the Levy Control Framework.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We would be glad to provide further input should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the committee require.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><br /><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Corbel; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Corbel; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>